{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08a3778e-4d0f-4dd2-a67b-a23efe69b4b4","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n**Why:** After a .NET SDK update, your installed workloads (like `maui`) may be pinned to versions that are incompatible with the new SDK. `dotnet workload update` pulls the latest workload versions that match your current SDK band.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the already-installed versions — it fixes corrupted installations but won't bump workloads to versions compatible with a newer SDK.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build   # verify the build works again\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues after updating, `dotnet workload list` will show what's installed, and you can reinstall a specific workload with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13aa31a9-8d28-4473-95fa-1fad8d5ecbab","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for your SDK band. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workloads need to match the new SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations. It doesn't change versions, just re-downloads and reinstalls the current versions.\n\n\nSo `dotnet workload update` is the right move here — it'll sync your workloads with the new SDK version and get your build working again.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"9424:60DE9:13B54BF:161BBE6:6A066FFF"},"id":"19f7ade9-1791-418d-8d37-b382dcc85452","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:59:52.905Z","parentId":"675b285a-4c3a-4af4-97c9-2c3b4838a934"}
